# REST Modules

This directory contains all HTTP API endpoint modules. Each subdirectory is a self-contained feature module.

## Module File Structure

Every REST module must contain exactly these three files:

```
<feature>/
├── <feature>.controller.ts   # Route handlers, Swagger decorators
├── <feature>.service.ts      # Business logic
└── <feature>.module.ts       # NestJS module registration
```

Additional service files are allowed when a module has multiple controllers (e.g., `render-trending-results.service.ts` alongside `trending-products.service.ts`).

## Controller Rules

### Swagger — mandatory on every controller and route

Apply `@ApiTags` at the class level. Apply `@ApiOperation` and one `@ApiResponse` per possible HTTP status on every route handler. Use `HttpStatus` enum from `@nestjs/common`, never raw numbers.

```typescript
import { Controller, Get, HttpStatus, Param, Query } from '@nestjs/common';
import { ApiOperation, ApiParam, ApiResponse, ApiTags } from '@nestjs/swagger';

import { ExampleService } from '@modules/rest/example/example.service';

import { LogExecution } from '@decorators/log-execution.decorator';

import { ExampleQueryDto } from '@dto/example/example-query.dto';
import { ExampleResponseDto } from '@dto/example/example-response.dto';

@ApiTags('Example')
@Controller('example')
export class ExampleController {
	constructor(private readonly exampleService: ExampleService) {}

	@Get(':id')
	@ApiOperation({ summary: 'Get example by ID' })
	@ApiParam({ name: 'id', type: String, description: 'Example ID' })
	@ApiResponse({
		status: HttpStatus.OK,
		description: 'Returns the example',
		type: ExampleResponseDto,
	})
	@ApiResponse({ status: HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND, description: 'Example not found' })
	@ApiResponse({ status: HttpStatus.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR, description: 'Internal server error' })
	@LogExecution({
		paramFormatter: (params: [string, ExampleQueryDto]) => ({ id: params[0], query: params[1] }),
		responseFormatter: (res: ExampleResponseDto) => ({ count: res.items.length }),
	})
	async getExample(
		@Param('id') id: string,
		@Query() query: ExampleQueryDto,
	): Promise<ExampleResponseDto> {
		return this.exampleService.getExample(id, query);
	}
}
```

### Guards

Apply guards at the controller class level with `@UseGuards`. Only apply at the route level when a single route within an otherwise unguarded controller needs protection — this is the exception, not the rule.

```typescript
// Class-level guard — preferred when all routes need protection
@UseGuards(InternalVpnAccessGuard)
@Controller('admin')
export class AdminController { ... }

// Route-level guard — only when one route in a controller needs different protection
@Controller('trending-products')
export class TrendingProductsDashboardController {
	@Get('dashboard')
	@UseGuards(InternalVpnAccessGuard)
	getDashboard(): void { ... }
}
```

### `@LogExecution` on controller methods

Apply `@LogExecution` with `paramFormatter` and `responseFormatter` on every public route handler. Keep response formatters lean — log counts or identifiers, not full payloads.

```typescript
@LogExecution({
	paramFormatter: (params: [string]) => ({ id: params[0] }),
	responseFormatter: (res: ExampleResponseDto) => ({ count: res.items.length }),
})
async getExample(@Param('id') id: string): Promise<ExampleResponseDto> { ... }
```

## Service Rules

### Logger

Declare a private `logger` using `Logger` from `@nestjs/common`:

```typescript
@Injectable()
export class ExampleService {
	private readonly logger = new Logger(ExampleService.name);
}
```

### `@LogExecution` on public methods

Apply `@LogExecution` on all public methods. Use `responseFormatter` to avoid logging large payloads:

```typescript
@LogExecution({
	paramFormatter: (params) => params,
	responseFormatter: (res: ExampleResponseDto) => res.items.length,
})
async getExample(id: string, query: ExampleQueryDto): Promise<ExampleResponseDto> { ... }
```

## Module Registration Rules

Import only the modules the feature directly depends on. Never import `AppModule`. Declare the controller in `controllers`, the service in `providers`, and export the service if other modules need it.

```typescript
import { Module } from '@nestjs/common';

import { CacheModule } from '@modules/cache/cache.module';
import { DBModule } from '@modules/db/db.module';
import { EnvConfigModule } from '@modules/env-config/env-config.module';
import { ProductHydrationModule } from '@modules/product-hydration/product-hydration.module';
import { ExampleController } from '@modules/rest/example/example.controller';
import { ExampleService } from '@modules/rest/example/example.service';

@Module({
	imports: [CacheModule, DBModule, EnvConfigModule, ProductHydrationModule],
	controllers: [ExampleController],
	providers: [ExampleService],
	exports: [ExampleService],
})
export class ExampleModule {}
```

## DTO Rules

### Request DTOs

Use `class-validator` decorators for validation and `@ApiProperty` for Swagger documentation. Place in `src/dto/<feature>/` or in the module folder.

```typescript
import { ApiProperty } from '@nestjs/swagger';
import { Type } from 'class-transformer';
import { IsInt, IsOptional, Max, Min } from 'class-validator';

export class ExampleQueryDto {
	@ApiProperty({ description: 'Maximum results to return', required: false, default: 30, minimum: 1, maximum: 30 })
	@IsOptional()
	@IsInt({ message: 'Limit must be an integer' })
	@Min(1)
	@Max(30)
	@Type(() => Number)
	limit?: number = 30;
}
```

### Response DTOs

Annotate every property with `@ApiProperty`. Reference the DTO class in the `type` field of `@ApiResponse`.

```typescript
import { ApiProperty } from '@nestjs/swagger';

export class ExampleResponseDto {
	@ApiProperty({ description: 'List of items', type: [ItemDto] })
	items: ItemDto[];
}
```

